Let $h$ be the triangle's height, $g$ be $\triangle QPR$'s base, and $a$ be $\triangle PQR$'s area i.e. $a\geq 0$. The area of $\triangle QPR$ is $\frac{g\cdot h}{2}$, and since $g$ is an integer, $h=\frac{2a}{g}$, so
\begin{align*}
h = \frac{2\cdot 27}{g}\\
\end{align*}
Thus $h=\frac{54}{g}$. We note that $h=a/g$. Additionally, by the Arithmetic Mean-Geometric Mean Inequality, we have $g^2\geq 4a$. Since $g^2\geq 0$, we have $g\geq 6$. Applying this inequality to the above expression yields
\begin{align*}
6&>g\\
25&>g^2\\
25&>4a\\
a&<\frac{25}{4}\\
\end{align*}
In summary, we have found that
\begin{align*}
27&\geq a\\
a&>0\\
a&<\frac{25}{4}\approx 6.25\\
\end{align*}
Thus $\textbf{6.25}\!\leq a\!\leq\! 27$, and we reach a contradiction because $\triangle PQR$ has an area of 27 square centimeters. \end{align*}
<answer>The triangle does not exist. The height cannot be less than 2.5 “square base units,” and cannot be greater than 27 “square base units.”</answer>

